    <section id="research" style="background:#fff;border-radius:18px;padding:32px 28px;box-shadow:0 2px 12px rgba(59,130,246,0.06);">
      <h2 style="font-size:1.35rem;color:var(--primary-color);font-weight:800;margin-bottom:10px;">Research: Key Findings</h2>
      <ul style="font-size:1.07rem;color:var(--primary-dark);margin-left:18px;">
        <li><strong>Renters reform loophole:</strong> Most student accommodations are purpose-built and therefore not covered by the new bill protecting tenants.</li>
        <li><strong>Ground 4A vulnerability:</strong> If your house is full of students, your property can be repossessed in 4 months—landlords chose student renting because classification makes you an exploitative target.</li>
        <li><strong>No rent caps or fee limits:</strong> Purpose-built student accommodation run by private companies is not affected by rent caps and limited fees.</li>
        <li><strong>Lack of direct laws:</strong> There are no specific laws directly regulating student accommodation standards.</li>
        <li><strong>Manchester University case:</strong> Found to be keeping students in inadequate accommodation.</li>
        <li><strong>Channel 4 Investigation:</strong> Exposed poor conditions in student housing.</li>
      </ul>
      <div style="margin-top:16px;padding:14px;background:rgba(59,130,246,0.05);border-radius:10px;">
        <p style="font-size:1.05rem;color:var(--primary-dark);margin:0;"><strong>Proposed Solutions:</strong> Universities directly owning homes for student housing, campaigning for specific student accommodation laws.</p>
