    <section id="rating" style="background:#fff;border-radius:18px;padding:32px 28px;box-shadow:0 2px 12px rgba(59,130,246,0.06);">
      <h2 style="font-size:1.35rem;color:var(--primary-color);font-weight:800;margin-bottom:10px;">Rating System: Scores, Criteria, Action</h2>
      <p style="font-size:1.07rem;color:var(--primary-dark);margin-bottom:10px;">The rating system categories score a property based on whether they adhere to the different aspects of adequate housing, according to the definition provided by the UN Housing Ombudsman. These scores are then ranked on a colour-coded scale, giving a quantifiable ranking of how adequate the property is, akin to the food safety rating given to restaurants and food vendors.</p>
      
      <div style="margin:18px 0 0 0;font-size:1.07rem;color:var(--primary-color);">
        <strong>Score out of 10:</strong><br>
        <span style="color:#10b981;font-weight:700;">9+: Excellent</span><br>
        <span style="color:#3b82f6;font-weight:700;">7-8: Good</span><br>
        <span style="color:#f59e42;font-weight:700;">5-6: Fair</span><br>
        <span style="color:#ef4444;font-weight:700;">3-4: Poor</span><br>
        <span style="color:#7c3aed;font-weight:700;">1-2: Inadequate</span>
      </div>
      
      <p style="margin-top:14px;color:var(--text-secondary);font-size:1.05rem;">This ranking can then be used by the property owner as a way to advertise the property in a more positive light, bring attention to residential areas that are struggling to meet the requirements, or highlight properties that deserve recognition.</p>
      
      <p style="margin-top:14px;color:var(--primary-dark);font-size:1.05rem;">Our system relies on a brief questionnaire of 10 yes or no questions that are each based on different aspects of the definition of adequate housing, and then graded based on how many they comply with. Each question will also have an optional short freeform box for expansion on any specific issues a property has.</p>
    </section>

